<TITLE> China says willing to resume rights dialogue with US </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 BEIJING, Feb 26 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - China is willing to resume a human rights dialogue with the United States, its foreign minister said on Tuesday following talks with US Secretary of State Condoleezza Rice. China broke off the dialogue in 2004 after Washington urged a UN watchdog to condemn what it called China's backsliding on rights, but Yang's comments could be aimed at defusing criticism surrounding Beijing's hosting of the 2008 Olympics. "We are ready to resume the human rights dialogue," Chinese Foreign Minister Yang Jiechi told reporters at a news conference with Rice, who was in Beijing on a one-day visit. Rights groups have been using the Games to put pressure on China, which they say is the world's leading jailer of journalists and which lacks an independent judiciary, cracks down on political dissent and strictly controls the media. Rice said she raised the issues with Yang. "I have expressed to the minister our continuing concerns about human rights and religious freedom in China (and) the importance of resuming a human rights dialogue between the United States and China," she told a joint news conference. "We do this in a spirit of respect but these issues are very near and dear to America," she added. New York-based Human Rights Watch had urged Rice to speak publicly about press freedom and dissent on her trip. The group mentioned several cases, including that of activist Hu Jia, detained for inciting subversion after supporting campaigns for democratic reform, and Yang Chunlin, a factory worker on trial after calling for rights to take precedence over the Olympics. It was not clear if Rice raised any specific cases with Yang or other Chinese leaders during her vis
